e investing in the organization. This innovative change in accounting can lead to a fundamentally different perspective on the value of an organization. Through case studies of organizations that have implemented social accounting in the United States, Canada, India, and Scotland, Accounting for Social Value provides a unique perspective for understanding key issues in this growing field.Building on two related titles, Researching the Social Economy (2010) and Businesses with a Difference (2012), Accounting for Social Value offers academics, accountants, policy-developers, and members of non-profit, co-operative, and for-profit organizations tools and insights to explore the connections between economic, social, and environmental dimensions. The lessons learned are valuable not only for other social economy organizations, but also for organizations in the public and for-profit sectors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aEnvironmental economics. 0aSocial accounting. 0aSocial entrepreneurship. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBebbington, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherkil, Manjula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aContrafatto, Massimo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHicks, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Edward T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcmurtry, J.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedalye, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab